VALUES
(40, 20, 12, 38, 7, 3, 5, NULL, 'Equality in Labor and Fasting', 'This connection highlights the theme of equal treatment in both passages. In Matthew, those who worked less receive the same reward, paralleling Zechariah''s inquiry about the sincerity of fasting practices over time.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 13, 40, 26, 50, 50, 'Friend', 'Addressing ''Friend'' in Context', 'Both passages emphasize the term ''Friend'' as a significant address. In Matthew 20:13, it is used in a context of agreement, while in Matthew 26:50, it is used in a moment of betrayal.', 'keyword', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 13, 40, 22, 12, 12, 'Friend', 'Friendship and Accountability', 'Both passages emphasize the term ''Friend,'' highlighting a relational dynamic. Additionally, they address accountability regarding agreements and expectations, as seen in the responses to the characters in each scenario.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 13, 45, 9, 14, 15, NULL, 'Divine Mercy and Justice', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s mercy and justice. Both passages address the idea of fairness in God''s dealings, with Matthew emphasizing agreement and Romans discussing God''s sovereign choice in mercy.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 13, 1, 18, 25, 25, 'didst not thou agree with me', 'Justice and Agreement Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of justice and fairness in both passages. In Matthew, the landowner asserts he has not wronged the workers, paralleling the assertion in Genesis that the Judge of all the earth will do right.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 13, 18, 34, 8, 12, 'didst not thou agree with me', 'Justice and Fairness in God', 'This connection highlights the theme of justice and fairness in both passages. In Matthew, the landowner asserts he has done no wrong, paralleling Job''s assertion that God does not commit iniquity or pervert judgment.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 13, 18, 34, 17, 18, NULL, 'Justice and Agreement in Context', 'This connection highlights the theme of justice and fairness in both passages. In Matthew, the laborer questions the fairness of his wage, while Job discusses the nature of justice in governance, suggesting that those in authority should be just.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 13, 45, 9, 20, 20, 'didst not thou agree with me', 'Divine Authority and Human Response', 'This connection highlights the theme of questioning authority. Both passages emphasize the relationship between the creator and the created, with humans challenging divine decisions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 14, 42, 15, 31, 31, 'thine', 'Inheritance and Generosity', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of sharing and generosity in relation to inheritance. The phrases ''thine'' and ''is thine'' highlight the notion of what belongs to the individuals and the equal distribution of resources.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 14, 43, 17, 2, 2, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Generosity', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine generosity in giving. Both passages emphasize the idea of giving to others, with the last receiving the same as the first and eternal life being given to many.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 14, 12, 10, 30, 31, NULL, 'Divine Favor and Human Response', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine favor given to individuals despite their shortcomings. Both passages emphasize God''s willingness to reward actions, yet also point to the failure to fully adhere to His commands.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 14, 26, 29, 18, 20, 'I will give unto this last', 'Wages for Labor Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of receiving wages for labor. In both passages, there is an emphasis on giving what is due for work performed, whether it be the laborers in the vineyard or Nebuchadrezzar''s army.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 14, 40, 6, 2, 2, NULL, 'Reward and Generosity Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of reward in both passages. In Matthew 20:14, the emphasis is on giving equally to all, while Matthew 6:2 warns against seeking glory from men for acts of generosity.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 14, 40, 6, 16, 16, 'I will give unto this last', 'Reward and Attitude in Service', 'Both passages emphasize the nature of reward based on one''s actions and attitude. In Matthew 20:14, the focus is on the last receiving the same as the first, while Matthew 6:16 highlights the hypocrites receiving their reward for outward appearances.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 14, 45, 3, 4, 4, NULL, 'Divine Justice and Equality', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s justice in rewarding individuals according to His will. Both passages emphasize that God''s decisions may challenge human expectations of fairness, as seen in the equal treatment of the last and the first.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 15, 45, 9, 15, 24, 'Is thine eye evil, because I am good?', 'Divine Sovereignty and Mercy', 'Both passages emphasize God''s authority to show mercy and compassion as He wills. Matthew 20:15 questions the fairness of God''s goodness, while Romans 9:15-24 elaborates on God''s sovereign choice in dispensing mercy.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 15, 5, 15, 9, 9, 'thine eye evil', 'Evil Eye and Goodness', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of an ''evil eye'' in relation to goodness. Matthew addresses the perception of envy towards goodness, while Deuteronomy warns against harboring wicked thoughts that lead to neglecting the poor.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 15, 32, 4, 1, 4, 'I am good', 'God''s Goodness and Human Anger', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s goodness provoking human anger. In both passages, the question of divine mercy leads to a human response of displeasure, as seen in Jonah''s anger and the challenge in Matthew about the goodness of God.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 15, 40, 6, 23, 23, 'thine eye evil', 'Evil Eye and Goodness', 'This connection highlights the concept of an ''evil eye'' in both passages, where the perception of goodness can lead to darkness. Both verses emphasize the moral implications of one''s perspective and attitude towards goodness.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 15, 41, 7, 22, 22, NULL, 'Evil Eye Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of an ''evil eye.'' In Matthew, the phrase suggests a negative perception of goodness, while in Mark, it is listed among other sinful behaviors.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 15, 43, 17, 2, 2, 'I am good', 'Divine Authority and Goodness', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority and goodness. In Matthew, the question of lawful action reflects God''s sovereignty, while in John, the power given to Jesus emphasizes His role in granting eternal life, showcasing the goodness of God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 15, 2, 33, 19, 19, NULL, 'Divine Goodness and Sovereignty', 'Both passages emphasize God''s goodness and His sovereign choice in dispensing grace and mercy. The phrase ''I will do what I will'' in Matthew parallels the declaration of God''s freedom to show mercy in Exodus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 16, 40, 19, 30, 30, 'the last shall be first', 'Reversal of Status Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the reversal of status, where the last become first and the first become last. This connection highlights a consistent theme of divine selection and the unexpected nature of God''s kingdom.', 'theme', 0.496, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 16, 41, 10, 31, 31, 'the last shall be first', 'Reversal of Status Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the reversal of status, where those who are last will be first and vice versa. This theme highlights the unexpected nature of God''s kingdom and the values it upholds.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 16, 40, 22, 14, 14, 'for many be called, but few chosen', 'Connection of Calling and Choosing', 'Both passages emphasize the idea that many are called, but few are chosen. This connection highlights the theme of divine selection and the reversal of expectations.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 16, 42, 13, 28, 30, 'the last shall be first, and the first last', 'Connection of Last and First', 'Both passages emphasize the reversal of status, where the last become first and the first become last. This theme highlights the unexpected nature of God''s kingdom and the inclusion of those previously marginalized.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 16, 42, 15, 7, 7, 'the last shall be first', 'Joy in Repentance and Reversal', 'Both passages emphasize a reversal of status, where the last are prioritized and the joy over one sinner''s repentance surpasses that of the righteous. This connection highlights the value placed on those who are often overlooked or considered last.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 16, 45, 8, 30, 30, 'many be called, but few chosen', 'Calling and Justification Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being called. Matthew highlights the distinction between those called and chosen, while Romans outlines the progression from calling to justification.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 16, 45, 9, 30, 30, 'the last shall be first', 'Righteousness and Divine Choice', 'Both passages emphasize the reversal of expectations in God''s plan. Matthew highlights that the last shall be first, while Romans illustrates how Gentiles, not initially pursuing righteousness, attain it through faith.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 17, 41, 10, 32, 34, 'going up to Jerusalem', 'Journey to Jerusalem', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus going up to Jerusalem with his disciples. They highlight the preparation for his impending suffering and death, indicating a shared narrative focus on this significant journey.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
